of life.
37. What, according to the text, is the key
motivation for Shona sculpture?
A The commercial potential of African sculpture in
the western art world.
B The religious idea that rocks are inhabited by
specific spiritual beings.
C The striking colours and shapes of many rocks in
the Inyanga Mountains.
D The amazing individual creativity of present-day
Zimbabwean artists.
38. Which of the following statements is most
in line with the text?
A Modern Shona sculpture seems to be related to
other artistic expressions from older times.
B Sculptural ornamentation was a prominent
feature of Great Zimbabwe.
C Traditional images of mysterious beasts are a permanent source of inspiration for Shona sculptors.
D The mythical city of Great Zimbabwe was full of
impressive bird statues.
39. What are we told about the muvesis in
comparison with present-day Shona
artists?
A Today’s Shona sculpture has further developed
the practical aims of the muvesis.
B The dream element of today’s Shona sculpture
was largely missing from the objects created by
the muvesis.
C Basically the same materials were used by the
muvesis as by recent Shona sculptors.
D The artistic work of the muvesis was more closely
related to everyday life than that of modern Shona
sculptors.
